Abby Gallows—born Abigail Callow—was a spirited young girl known in the 1890s for causing mischief, skipping church, and sneaking out after dark. “She was such an imp,” remembered her mother, Irene Callow, in a rare interview. “That’s why we thought for so long that it must be a prank she was playing, because she was upset that her brother was getting all of the attention. I’ve never stopped waiting for her to come home. Like nothing ever happened. It would be so like her.” But Abby never did come home. One evening, she vanished without a trace. The last person to see her was her younger brother, who claimed she walked into the woods, hand-in-hand with a tall man in a long dark coat, down a strange road of stone bricks that faded into the fog. That road was never found again. In the decades since, sightings of a ghostly girl wandering the edge of the woods have persisted. Some say they’ve heard laughter near the old creek bed at dusk. Others report seeing a pale figure standing motionless between the trees—always watching, always silent. Sometimes the figure is that of the young girl. Sometimes, its the figure of something more [[dangerous|the beast]] . The legend of Abby Gallows has become deeply rooted in local tradition. Every October, residents decorate their porches with hand-painted signs reading “Abby, come home” or hang tiny black coats in trees to represent the mysterious figure she followed. Children carve pumpkins with foggy roads and leave them at the forest’s edge, hoping Abby might find her way back. Whether ghost or memory, prankster or wanderer, Abby Gallows remains part of who we are—a chilling reminder that some stories never quite end.**]|= test =| <img
